# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: nist-cybersecurity-framework
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] To standardize this discipline, academics and professionals collaborate to offer guidance, policies, and industry standards on passwords, antivirus software, firewalls, encryption software, legal liability, security awareness and training, and so forth.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] This standardization may be further driven by a wide variety of laws and regulations that affect how data is accessed, processed, stored, transferred, and destroyed.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] While paper-based business operations are still prevalent, requiring their own set of information security practices, enterprise digital initiatives are increasingly being emphasized, with information assurance dealt with by information technology (IT) security specialists.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] These specialists apply information security to technology (most often some form of computer system).
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] IT security specialists are hired by major enterprise/establishment to keep company technology secure from malicious attacks seeking to acquire critical private information or gain control of the internal systems.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] There are many specialist roles in Information Security including securing networks and allied infrastructure, securing applications and databases, security testing, information systems auditing, business continuity planning, electronic record discovery, and digital forensics.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Information security standards are guidelines generally outlined in published materials that aim to protect a user's or an organization's cyber environment from threats.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] This environment includes the users themselves, hardware such as devices and networks, software such as applications or services, and any information in storage or transit.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] These standards comprise security concepts, technologies, and guidelines to deal with an adverse event.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] They may also include assessment criteria and certification for organizations implementing a minimum level of security.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] These standards are developed by various international and national bodies to prevent or mitigate cyber-attacks, ensure consistency among developers, and establish a minimum standard in industries susceptible to an attack.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The ISO/IEC 27000 family, published by the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) and the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), provides information about the guidelines and requirements for an Information Security Management System (ISMS).
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The Common Criteria (ISO/IEC 15408) provides guidelines on evaluating and certifying the security of a system.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The IEC 62443 establishes security standards for automation and control systems.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Similarly, the ISO/SAE 21434, ETSI EN 303 645, and EN 18031 provide standards for road vehicles, the Internet of Things, and radio-based systems respectively.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The NIST Cybersecurity Framework (NIST CSF) is a set of guidelines developed by the U.S.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] National Institute of Standards and Technology to help organizations with risk management.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] NIST also publishes various Federal Information Processing Standards (FIPS) and Special Publications.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The United Kingdom has introduced Cyber Essentials, which is a certification scheme to protect organizations against common security threats.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The Australian Cyber Security Centre publishes the Essential Eight mitigation strategies.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) regulates handling of cardholder data in order to reduce credit card fraud.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] UL has published standards related to specific industries such as UL 2900-2-3 for security and life safety signaling systems and UL-2900-2-1 for healthcare and wellness systems.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Information security threats come in many different forms.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Some of the most common threats today are software attacks, theft of intellectual property, theft of identity, theft of equipment or information, sabotage, and information extortion.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Viruses, worms, phishing attacks, and Trojan horses are a few common examples of software attacks.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The theft of intellectual property has also been an extensive issue for many businesses.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Identity theft is the attempt to act as someone else usually to obtain that person's personal information or to take advantage of their access to vital information through social engineering.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Sabotage usually consists of the destruction of an organization's website in an attempt to cause loss of confidence on the part of its customers.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Information extortion consists of theft of a company's property or information as an attempt to receive a payment in exchange for returning the information or property back to its owner, as with ransomware.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] One of the most functional precautions against these attacks is to conduct periodical user awareness.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Governments, military, corporations, financial institutions, hospitals, non-profit organizations, and private businesses amass a great deal of confidential information about their employees, customers, products, research, and financial status.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Should confidential information about a business's customers or finances or new product line fall into the hands of a competitor or hacker, a business and its customers could suffer widespread, irreparable financial loss, as well as damage to the company's reputation.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] From a business perspective, information security must be balanced against cost; the Gordon-Loeb Model provides a mathematical economic approach for addressing this concern.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] For the individual, information security has a significant effect on privacy, which is viewed very differently in various cultures.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Since the early days of communication, diplomats and military commanders understood that it was necessary to provide some mechanism to protect the confidentiality of correspondence and to have some means of detecting tampering.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Julius Caesar is credited with the invention of the Caesar cipher c.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] 50 B.C., which was created in order to prevent his secret messages from being read should a message fall into the wrong hands.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] However, for the most part protection was achieved through the application of procedural handling controls.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Sensitive information was marked up to indicate that it should be protected and transported by trusted persons, guarded and stored in a secure environment or strong box.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] As postal services expanded, governments created official organizations to intercept, decipher, read, and reseal letters (e.g., the U.K.'s Secret Office, founded in 1653).
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] In the mid-nineteenth century more complex classification systems were developed to allow governments to manage their information according to the degree of sensitivity.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] For example, the British Government codified this, to some extent, with the publication of the Official Secrets Act in 1889.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Section 1 of the law concerned espionage and unlawful disclosures of information, while Section 2 dealt with breaches of official trust.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] A public interest defense was soon added to defend disclosures in the interest of the state.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] A similar law was passed in India in 1889, The Indian Official Secrets Act, which was associated with the British colonial era and used to crack down on newspapers that opposed the Raj's policies.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] A newer version was passed in 1923 that extended to all matters of confidential or secret information for governance.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] By the time of the First World War, multi-tier classification systems were used to communicate information to and from various fronts, which encouraged greater use of code making and breaking sections in diplomatic and military headquarters.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Encoding became more sophisticated between the wars as machines were employed to scramble and unscramble information.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The establishment of computer security inaugurated the history of information security.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The need for such appeared during World War II.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The volume of information shared by the Allied countries during the Second World War necessitated formal alignment of classification systems and procedural controls.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] An arcane range of markings evolved to indicate who could handle documents (usually officers rather than enlisted troops) and where they should be stored as increasingly complex safes and storage facilities were developed.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The Enigma Machine, which was employed by the Germans to encrypt the data of warfare and was successfully decrypted by Alan Turing, can be regarded as a striking example of creating and using secured information.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Procedures evolved to ensure documents were destroyed properly, and it was the failure to follow these procedures which led to some of the greatest intelligence coups of the war (e.g., the capture of U-570).
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Various mainframe computers were connected online during the Cold War to complete more sophisticated tasks, in a communication process easier than mailing magnetic tapes back and forth by computer centers.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] As such, the Advanced Research Projects Agency (ARPA), of the United States Department of Defense, started researching the feasibility of a networked system of communication to trade information within the United States Armed Forces.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] In 1968, the ARPANET project was formulated by Larry Roberts, which would later evolve into what is known as the internet.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Hackers had effortless access to ARPANET, as phone numbers were known by the public.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Due to these problems, coupled with the constant violation of computer security, as well as the exponential increase in the number of hosts and users of the system, "network security" was often alluded to as "network insecurity".
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The end of the twentieth century and the early years of the twenty-first century saw rapid advancements in telecommunications, computing hardware and software, and data encryption.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The availability of smaller, more powerful, and less expensive computing equipment made electronic data processing within the reach of small business and home users.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The establishment of Transfer Control Protocol/Internetwork Protocol (TCP/IP) in the early 1980s enabled different types of computers to communicate.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] These computers quickly became interconnected through the internet.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The rapid growth and widespread use of electronic data processing and electronic business conducted through the internet, along with numerous occurrences of international terrorism, fueled the need for better methods of protecting the computers and the information they store, process, and transmit.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The academic disciplines of computer security and information assurance emerged along with numerous professional organizations, all sharing the common goals of ensuring the security and reliability of information systems.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The "CIA triad" of ***c**onfidentiality, **i**ntegrity, and **a**vailability* is at the heart of information security.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The concept was introduced in the Anderson Report in 1972 and later repeated in *The Protection of Information in Computer Systems.* The abbreviation was coined by Steve Lipner around 1986.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] In information security, confidentiality "is the property, that information is not made available or disclosed to unauthorized individuals, entities, or processes." While similar to "privacy", the two words are not interchangeable.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Rather, confidentiality is a component of privacy that is implemented to protect data from unauthorized viewers.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Examples of confidentiality of electronic data being compromised include laptop theft, password theft, or sensitive emails being sent to the incorrect individuals.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] In IT security, data integrity means maintaining and assuring the accuracy and completeness of data.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] This means that data cannot be modified in an unauthorized or undetected manner.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] More broadly, integrity is an information security principle that involves human/social, process, and commercial integrity, as well as data integrity.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] As such it touches on aspects such as credibility, consistency, truthfulness, completeness, accuracy, timeliness, and assurance.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] For any information system to serve its purpose, the information must be available when it is needed.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] This means the computing systems used to store and process the information, the security controls used to protect it, and the communication channels used to access it must be functioning correctly.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Ensuring availability may also involve preventing denial-of-service attacks, such as a flood of incoming messages to the target system, essentially forcing it to shut down.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] In addition to the classic CIA triad of security goals, some organisations may want to include security goals such as authenticity, accountability, non-repudiation, and reliability.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The merits of the Parkerian Hexad are a subject of debate amongst security professionals.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Risk is the likelihood that something bad will happen that causes harm to an informational asset (or the loss of the asset).
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] A vulnerability is a weakness that could be used to endanger or cause harm to an informational asset.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] A threat is anything (man-made or act of nature) that has the potential to cause harm.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The likelihood that a threat will use a vulnerability to cause harm creates a risk.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] When a threat does use a vulnerability to inflict harm, it has an impact.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] In the context of information security, the impact is a loss of availability, integrity, and confidentiality, and possibly other losses (lost income, loss of life, loss of real property).
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] There are two things in this definition that may need some clarification.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] First, the *process* of risk management is an ongoing, iterative process.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The business environment is constantly changing and new threats and vulnerabilities emerge every day.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Second, the choice of countermeasures (controls) used to manage risks must strike a balance between productivity, cost, effectiveness of the countermeasure, and the value of the informational asset being protected.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Furthermore, these processes have limitations as security breaches are generally rare and emerge in a specific context which may not be easily duplicated.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Thus, any process and countermeasure should itself be evaluated for vulnerabilities.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] It is not possible to identify all risks, nor is it possible to eliminate all risk.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The remaining risk is called "residual risk".
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] A risk assessment is carried out by a team of people who have knowledge of specific areas of the business.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Membership of the team may vary over time as different parts of the business are assessed.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The assessment may use a subjective qualitative analysis based on informed opinion, or where reliable dollar figures and historical information is available, the analysis may use quantitative analysis.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Research has shown that the most vulnerable point in most information systems is the human user, operator, designer, or other human.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Include: Acts of nature, acts of war, accidents, malicious acts originating from inside or outside the organization.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Conduct a vulnerability assessment, and for each vulnerability, calculate the probability that it will be exploited.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Evaluate policies, procedures, standards, training, physical security, quality control, technical security.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Calculate the impact that each threat would have on each asset.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Use qualitative analysis or quantitative analysis.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Identify, select and implement appropriate controls.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Consider productivity, cost effectiveness, and value of the asset.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Evaluate the effectiveness of the control measures.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Ensure the controls provide the required cost effective protection without discernible loss of productivity.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] For any given risk, management can choose to accept the risk based upon the relative low value of the asset, the relative low frequency of occurrence, and the relative low impact on the business.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Or, leadership may choose to mitigate the risk by selecting and implementing appropriate control measures to reduce the risk.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] In some cases, the risk can be transferred to another business by buying insurance or outsourcing to another business.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The reality of some risks may be disputed.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] In such cases leadership may choose to deny the risk.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Selecting and implementing proper security controls will initially help an organization bring down risk to acceptable levels.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Control selection should follow and should be based on the risk assessment.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Controls can vary in nature, but fundamentally they are ways of protecting the confidentiality, integrity or availability of information.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] ISO/IEC 27001 has defined controls in different areas.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Organizations can implement additional controls according to requirement of the organization.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] ISO/IEC 27002 offers a guideline for organizational information security standards.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Defense in depth is a fundamental security philosophy that relies on overlapping security systems designed to maintain protection even if individual components fail.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Rather than depending on a single security measure, it combines multiple layers of security controls both in the cloud and at network endpoints.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] This approach includes combinations like firewalls with intrusion-detection systems, email filtering services with desktop anti-virus, and cloud-based security alongside traditional network defenses.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The concept can be implemented through three distinct layers of administrative, logical, and physical controls, or visualized as an onion model with data at the core, surrounded by people, network security, host-based security, and application security layers.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The strategy emphasizes that security involves not just technology, but also people and processes working together, with real-time monitoring and response being crucial components.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] An important aspect of information security and risk management is recognizing the value of information and defining appropriate procedures and protection requirements for the information.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Not all information is equal and so not all information requires the same degree of protection.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] This requires information to be assigned a security classification.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The first step in information classification is to identify a member of senior management as the owner of the particular information to be classified.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The policy should describe the different classification labels, define the criteria for information to be assigned a particular label, and list the required security controls for each classification.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Some factors that influence which classification information should be assigned include how much value that information has to the organization, how old the information is and whether or not the information has become obsolete.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Laws and other regulatory requirements are also important considerations when classifying information.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] All employees in the organization, as well as business partners, must be trained on the classification schema and understand the required security controls and handling procedures for each classification.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Access to protected information must be restricted to people who are authorized to access the information.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The computer programs, and in many cases the computers that process the information, must also be authorized.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] This requires that mechanisms be in place to control the access to protected information.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The sophistication of the access control mechanisms should be in parity with the value of the information being protected; the more sensitive or valuable the information the stronger the control mechanisms need to be.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The foundation on which access control mechanisms are built start with identification and authentication.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Access control is generally considered in three steps: identification, authentication, and authorization.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Identification is an assertion of who someone is or what something is.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] If a person makes the statement "Hello, my name is John Doe" they are making a claim of who they are.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] However, their claim may or may not be true.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Before John Doe can be granted access to protected information it will be necessary to verify that the person claiming to be John Doe really is John Doe.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Typically the claim is in the form of a username.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] By entering that username, John Doe is claiming that they are the person to whom the username belongs.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Authentication is the act of verifying a claim of identity.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] When John Doe goes into a bank to make a withdrawal, he tells the bank teller he is John Doe, a claim of identity.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The bank teller asks to see a photo ID, so he hands the teller his driver's license.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The bank teller checks the license to make sure it has John Doe printed on it and compares the photograph on the license against the person claiming to be John Doe.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] If the photo and name match the person, then the teller has authenticated that John Doe is who he claimed to be.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Similarly, by entering the correct password, the user is providing evidence that he/she is the person the username belongs to.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Strong authentication requires providing more than one type of authentication information (two-factor authentication).
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The username is the most common form of identification on computer systems today and the password is the most common form of authentication.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Usernames and passwords have served their purpose, but they are increasingly inadequate.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Usernames and passwords are slowly being replaced or supplemented with more sophisticated authentication mechanisms such as time-based one-time password algorithms.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] After a person, program or computer has successfully been identified and authenticated then it must be determined what informational resources they are permitted to access and what actions they will be allowed to perform (run, view, create, delete, or change).
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Authorization to access information and other computing services begins with administrative policies and procedures.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The policies prescribe what information and computing services can be accessed, by whom, and under what conditions.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The access control mechanisms are then configured to enforce these policies.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Different computing systems are equipped with different kinds of access control mechanisms.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Some may even offer a choice of different access control mechanisms.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The access control mechanism a system offers will be based upon one of three approaches to access control, or it may be derived from a combination of the three approaches.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The non-discretionary approach consolidates all access control under a centralized administration.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The access to information and other resources is usually based on the individuals function (role) in the organization or the tasks the individual must perform.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The discretionary approach gives the creator or owner of the information resource the ability to control access to those resources.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] In the mandatory access control approach, access is granted or denied basing upon the security classification assigned to the information resource.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] To be effective, policies and other security controls must be enforceable and upheld.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Effective policies ensure that people are held accountable for their actions.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Treasury's guidelines for systems processing sensitive or proprietary information, for example, states that all failed and successful authentication and access attempts must be logged, and all access to information must leave some type of audit trail.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Also, the need-to-know principle needs to be in effect when talking about access control.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] This principle gives access rights to a person to perform their job functions.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] This principle is used in the government when dealing with difference clearances.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Even though two employees in different departments have a top-secret clearance, they must have a need-to-know in order for information to be exchanged.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Within the need-to-know principle, network administrators grant the employee the least amount of privilege to prevent employees from accessing more than what they are supposed to.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Need-to-know helps to enforce the confidentiality-integrity-availability triad and directly impacts the confidential area of the triad.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Information security uses cryptography to transform usable information into a form that renders it unusable by anyone other than an authorized user; this process is called encryption.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Information that has been encrypted (rendered unusable) can be transformed back into its original usable form by an authorized user who possesses the cryptographic key, through the process of decryption.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Cryptography is used in information security to protect information from unauthorized or accidental disclosure while the information is in transit (either electronically or physically) and while information is in storage.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Cryptography provides information security with other useful applications as well, including improved authentication methods, message digests, digital signatures, non-repudiation, and encrypted network communications.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Older, less secure applications such as Telnet and File Transfer Protocol (FTP) are slowly being replaced with more secure applications such as Secure Shell (SSH) that use encrypted network communications.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Wireless communications can be encrypted using protocols such as WPA/WPA2 or the older (and less secure) WEP.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Wired communications (such as ITU‑T G.hn) are secured using AES for encryption and X.1035 for authentication and key exchange.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Software applications such as GnuPG or PGP can be used to encrypt data files and email.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Cryptography can introduce security problems when it is not implemented correctly.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Cryptographic solutions need to be implemented using industry-accepted solutions that have undergone rigorous peer review by independent experts in cryptography.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The length and strength of the encryption key is also an important consideration.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] A key that is weak or too short will produce weak encryption.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The keys used for encryption and decryption must be protected with the same degree of rigor as any other confidential information.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] They must be protected from unauthorized disclosure and destruction, and they must be available when needed.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Public key infrastructure (PKI) solutions address many of the problems that surround key management.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Federal Sentencing Guidelines now make it possible to hold corporate officers liable for failing to exercise due care and due diligence in the management of their information systems.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Attention should be made to two important points in these definitions.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] First, in due care, steps are taken to show; this means that the steps can be verified, measured, or even produce tangible artifacts.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Second, in due diligence, there are continual activities; this means that people are actually doing things to monitor and maintain the protection mechanisms, and these activities are ongoing.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Organizations have a responsibility with practicing duty of care when applying information security.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The Duty of Care Risk Analysis Standard (DoCRA) provides principles and practices for evaluating risk.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] It considers all parties that could be affected by those risks.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] DoCRA helps evaluate safeguards if they are appropriate in protecting others from harm while presenting a reasonable burden.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] With increased data breach litigation, companies must balance security controls, compliance, and its mission.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Computer security incident management is a specialized form of incident management focused on monitoring, detecting, and responding to security events on computers and networks in a predictable way.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Organizations implement this through incident response plans (IRPs) that are activated when security breaches are detected.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] These plans typically involve an incident response team (IRT) with specialized skills in areas like penetration testing, computer forensics, and network security.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Change management is a formal process for directing and controlling alterations to the information processing environment.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] This includes alterations to desktop computers, the network, servers, and software.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The objectives of change management are to reduce the risks posed by changes to the information processing environment and improve the stability and reliability of the processing environment as changes are made.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] It is not the objective of change management to prevent or hinder necessary changes from being implemented.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Any change to the information processing environment introduces an element of risk.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Even apparently simple changes can have unexpected effects.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] One of management's many responsibilities is the management of risk.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Change management is a tool for managing the risks introduced by changes to the information processing environment.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Part of the change management process ensures that changes are not implemented at inopportune times when they may disrupt critical business processes or interfere with other changes being implemented.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Some kinds of changes are a part of the everyday routine of information processing and adhere to a predefined procedure, which reduces the overall level of risk to the processing environment.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Creating a new user account or deploying a new desktop computer are examples of changes that do not generally require change management.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] However, relocating user file shares, or upgrading the Email server pose a much higher level of risk to the processing environment and are not a normal everyday activity.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The critical first steps in change management are (a) defining change (and communicating that definition) and (b) defining the scope of the change system.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Change management is usually overseen by a change review board composed of representatives from key business areas, security, networking, systems administrators, database administration, application developers, desktop support, and the help desk.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The tasks of the change review board can be facilitated with the use of automated work flow application.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The responsibility of the change review board is to ensure the organization's documented change management procedures are followed.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Change management procedures that are simple to follow and easy to use can greatly reduce the overall risks created when changes are made to the information processing environment.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Good change management procedures improve the overall quality and success of changes as they are implemented.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] This is accomplished through planning, peer review, documentation, and communication.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] ISO/IEC 20000, The Visible OPS Handbook: Implementing ITIL in 4 Practical and Auditable Steps (Full book summary), and ITIL all provide valuable guidance on implementing an efficient and effective change management program information security.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Business continuity management (BCM) concerns arrangements aiming to protect an organization's critical business functions from interruption due to incidents, or at least minimize the effects.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] BCM is essential to any organization to keep technology and business in line with current threats to the continuation of business as usual.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] The BCM should be included in an organizations risk analysis plan to ensure that all of the necessary business functions have what they need to keep going in the event of any type of threat to any business function.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Whereas BCM takes a broad approach to minimizing disaster-related risks by reducing both the probability and the severity of incidents, a disaster recovery plan (DRP) focuses specifically on resuming business operations as quickly as possible after a disaster.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] A disaster recovery plan, invoked soon after a disaster occurs, lays out the steps necessary to recover critical information and communications technology (ICT) infrastructure.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Disaster recovery planning includes establishing a planning group, performing risk assessment, establishing priorities, developing recovery strategies, preparing inventories and documentation of the plan, developing verification criteria and procedure, and lastly implementing the plan.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Below is a partial listing of governmental laws and regulations in various parts of the world that have, had, or will have, a significant effect on data processing and information security.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Important industry sector regulations have also been included when they have a significant impact on information security.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p01] Andersson and Reimers (2019) report these certifications range from CompTIA's A+ and Security+ through the ICS2.org's CISSP, etc.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p02] Describing more than simply how security aware employees are, information security culture is the ideas, customs, and social behaviors of an organization that impact information security in both positive and negative ways.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p02] Cultural concepts can help different segments of the organization work effectively or work against effectiveness towards information security within an organization.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p02] The way employees think and feel about security and the actions they take can have a big impact on information security in organizations.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p02] Andersson and Reimers (2014) found that employees often do not see themselves as part of the organization Information Security "effort" and often take actions that ignore organizational information security best interests.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/information-security-p02] Research shows information security culture needs to be improved continuously.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/it-risk] Assessing the probability or likelihood of various types of event/incident with their predicted impacts or consequences, should they occur, is a common way to assess and measure IT risks.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/it-risk] Alternative methods of measuring IT risk typically involve assessing other contributory factors such as the threats, vulnerabilities, exposures, and asset values.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/it-risk] The uncertainty of loss expressed in terms of probability of such loss.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/it-risk] The probability that a hostile entity will successfully exploit a particular telecommunications or COMSEC system for intelligence purposes; its factors are threat and vulnerability.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/it-risk] A combination of the likelihood that a threat shall occur, the likelihood that a threat occurrence shall result in an adverse impact, and the severity of the resulting adverse impact.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/it-risk] 5. the probability that a particular threat will exploit a particular vulnerability of the system.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/it-risk] Many NIST publications define **risk** in IT context in different publications: FISMApedia term provide a list.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/it-risk] *the resulting impact if this should occur.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/it-risk] IT risk is the probable frequency and probable magnitude of future loss.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/it-risk] ISACA published the Risk IT Framework in order to provide an end-to-end, comprehensive view of all risks related to the use of IT.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/it-risk] You can't effectively and consistently manage what you can't measure, and you can't measure what you haven't defined.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/it-risk] Measuring IT risk (or cyber risk) can occur at many levels.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/it-risk] At a business level, the risks are managed categorically.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/it-risk] Front line IT departments and NOC's tend to measure more discrete, individual risks.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/it-risk] Managing the nexus between them is a key role for modern CISO's.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/it-risk] When measuring risk of any kind, selecting the correct equation for a given threat, asset, and available data is an important step.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/it-risk] Doing so is subject unto itself, but there are common components of risk equations that are helpful to understand.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/it-risk] The field of IT risk management has spawned a number of terms and techniques which are unique to the industry.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/it-risk] Some industry terms have yet to be reconciled.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/it-risk] For example, the term *vulnerability* is often used interchangeably with likelihood of occurrence, which can be problematic.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/it-risk] An identified occurrence of a system, service or network state indicating a possible breach of information security policy or failure of safeguards, or a previously unknown situation that may be security relevant.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/it-risk] An event [G.11] that has been assessed as having an actual or potentially adverse effect on the security or performance of a system.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/it-risk] The likelihood of a security incident occurrence is a function of the likelihood that a threat appears and the likelihood that the threat can successfully exploit the relevant system vulnerabilities.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/it-risk] The consequence of the occurrence of a security incident are a function of likely impact that the incident will have on the organization as a result of the harm the organization assets will sustain.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/it-risk] Harm is related to the value of the assets to the organization; the same asset can have different values to different organizations.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/it-risk] If numerical values (money for impact and probabilities for the other factors), the risk can be expressed in monetary terms and compared to the cost of countermeasures and the residual risk after applying the security control.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/it-risk] It is not always practical to express this values, so in the first step of risk evaluation, risk are graded dimensionless in three or five steps scales.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/it-risk] An IT risk management system (ITRMS) is a component of a broader enterprise risk management (ERM) system.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/it-risk] ITRMS are also integrated into broader information security management systems (ISMS).
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/it-risk] In the following a brief description of applicable rules organized by source.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/it-risk] As legislation evolves, there has been increased focus to require **'reasonable security'** for information management.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] The **National Institute of Standards and Technology** (**NIST**) is an agency of the United States Department of Commerce whose mission is to promote American innovation and industrial competitiveness.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] NIST's activities are organized into physical science laboratory programs that include nanoscale science and technology, engineering, information technology, neutron research, material measurement, and physical measurement.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] From 1901 to 1988, the agency was named the **National Bureau of Standards**.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] The NIST Historic District was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2021.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] Article 1, section 8, of the Constitution of the United States, ratified in 1789, granted these powers to the new Congress: "The Congress shall have power ...
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] To coin money, regulate the value thereof, and of foreign coin, and fix the standard of weights and measures".
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] In 1821, President John Quincy Adams declared, "Weights and measures may be ranked among the necessities of life to every individual of human society.".
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] Nevertheless, it was not until 1838 that the United States government adopted a uniform set of standards.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] In 1901, in response to a bill proposed by Congressman James H.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] Southard (R, Ohio), the Bureau of Standards was founded with the mandate to provide standard weights and measures, and to serve as the national physical laboratory for the United States.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] Southard had previously sponsored a bill for metric conversion of the United States.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] President Theodore Roosevelt appointed Samuel W.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] The budget for the first year of operation was $40,000.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] The Bureau took custody of the copies of the kilogram and meter bars that were the standards for US measures, and set up a program to provide metrology services for United States scientific and commercial users.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] A laboratory site was constructed in Washington, DC, and instruments were acquired from the national physical laboratories of Europe.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] In addition to weights and measures, the Bureau developed instruments for electrical units and for measurement of light.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] In 1905 a meeting was called that would be the first "National Conference on Weights and Measures".
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] Initially conceived as purely a metrology agency, the Bureau of Standards was directed by Herbert Hoover to set up divisions to develop commercial standards for materials and products.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] Some of these standards were for products intended for government use, but product standards also affected private-sector consumption.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] Quality standards were developed for products including some types of clothing, automobile brake systems and headlamps, antifreeze, and electrical safety.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] During World War I, the Bureau worked on multiple problems related to war production, even operating its own facility to produce optical glass when European supplies were cut off.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] Between the wars, Harry Diamond of the Bureau developed a blind approach radio aircraft landing system.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] In 1948, financed by the United States Air Force, the Bureau began design and construction of SEAC, the Standards Eastern Automatic Computer.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] The computer went into operation in May 1950 using a combination of vacuum tubes and solid-state diode logic.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] About the same time the Standards Western Automatic Computer, was built at the Los Angeles office of the NBS by Harry Huskey and used for research there.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] A mobile version, DYSEAC, was built for the Signal Corps in 1954.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] Due to a changing mission, the "National Bureau of Standards" became the "National Institute of Standards and Technology" in 1988.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] Following the September 11, 2001, attacks, under the National Construction Safety Team Act (NCST), NIST conducted the official investigation into the collapse of the World Trade Center buildings.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] Following the 2021 Surfside condominium building collapse, NIST sent engineers to the site to investigate the cause of the collapse.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] In 2019, NIST launched a program named NIST on a Chip to decrease the size of instruments from lab machines to chip size.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] Applications include aircraft testing, communication with satellites for navigation purposes, and temperature and pressure.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] In 2023, the Biden administration began plans to create a U.S.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] AI Safety Institute within NIST to coordinate AI safety matters.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] According to *The Washington Post*, NIST is considered "notoriously underfunded and understaffed", which could present an obstacle to these efforts.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] NIST, known between 1901 and 1988 as the National Bureau of Standards (NBS), is a measurement standards laboratory, also known as the National Metrological Institute (NMI), which is a non-regulatory agency of the United States Department of Commerce.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] NIST had an operating budget for fiscal year 2007 (October 1, 2006 – September 30, 2007) of about $843.3 million.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] NIST's 2009 budget was $992 million, and it also received $610 million as part of the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] NIST employs about 2,900 scientists, engineers, technicians, and support and administrative personnel.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] About 1,800 NIST associates (guest researchers and engineers from American companies and foreign countries) complement the staff.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] NIST partners with 1,400 manufacturing specialists and staff at nearly 350 affiliated centers around the country.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] NIST publishes the ***Handbook 44*** that provides the "Specifications, tolerances, and other technical requirements for weighing and measuring devices".
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] The Congress of 1866 made use of the metric system in commerce a legally protected activity through the passage of Metric Act of 1866.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] In May 1875, 17 out of 20 countries signed a document known as the *Metric Convention* or the *Treaty of the Meter*, which established the International Bureau of Weights and Measures under the control of an international committee elected by the General Conference on Weights and Measures.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] NIST is headquartered in Gaithersburg, Maryland, and operates a facility in Boulder, Colorado, which was dedicated by President Eisenhower in 1954.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] NIST's activities are organized into laboratory programs and extramural programs.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] Effective October 2010, NIST was realigned by reducing the number of NIST laboratory units from ten to six.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] NIST's Boulder laboratories are known for housing NIST‑F1, an atomic clock.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] NIST‑F1 serves as the source of the nation's official time.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] From its measurement of the natural resonance frequency of cesium—which defines the second—NIST broadcasts time signals via longwave radio station WWVB near Fort Collins, Colorado, and shortwave radio stations WWV and WWVH, located near Fort Collins and Kekaha, Hawaii, respectively.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] NIST also operates a neutron science user facility: the NIST Center for Neutron Research (NCNR).
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] The NCNR provides scientists access to a variety of neutron scattering instruments, which they use in many research fields (materials science, fuel cells, biotechnology, etc.).
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] The SURF III Synchrotron Ultraviolet Radiation Facility is a source of synchrotron radiation, in continuous operation since 1961.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] SURF III now serves as the US national standard for source-based radiometry throughout the generalized optical spectrum.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] All NASA-borne, extreme-ultraviolet observation instruments have been calibrated at SURF since the 1970s, and SURF is used for the measurement and characterization of systems for extreme ultraviolet lithography.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] The Center for Nanoscale Science and Technology (CNST) performs research in nanotechnology, both through internal research efforts and by running a user-accessible cleanroom nanomanufacturing facility.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] This "NanoFab" is equipped with tools for lithographic patterning and imaging (e.g., electron microscopes and atomic force microscopes).
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] As part of its mission, NIST supplies industry, academia, government, and other users with over 1,300 Standard Reference Materials (SRMs).
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] These artifacts are certified as having specific characteristics or component content, used as calibration standards for measuring equipment and procedures, quality control benchmarks for industrial processes, and experimental control samples.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] NIST publishes the *Handbook 44* each year after the annual meeting of the National Conference on Weights and Measures (NCWM).
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] Each edition is developed through cooperation of the **Committee on Specifications and Tolerances** of the NCWM and the **Weights and Measures Division** (WMD) of NIST.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] The purpose of the book is a partial fulfillment of the statutory responsibility for "cooperation with the states in securing uniformity of weights and measures laws and methods of inspection".
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] NIST has been publishing various forms of what is now the *Handbook 44* since 1918 and began publication under the current name in 1949.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] The 2010 edition conforms to the concept of the primary use of the SI (metric) measurements recommended by the Omnibus Foreign Trade and Competitiveness Act of 1988.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] NIST is developing government-wide identity document standards for federal employees and contractors to prevent unauthorized persons from gaining access to government buildings and computer systems.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] In 2002, the National Construction Safety Team Act mandated NIST to conduct an investigation into the collapse of the World Trade Center buildings 1 and 2 and the 47-story 7 World Trade Center.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] The "World Trade Center Collapse Investigation", directed by lead investigator Shyam Sunder, covered three aspects, including a technical building and fire safety investigation to study the factors contributing to the probable cause of the collapses of the WTC Towers (WTC 1 and 2) and WTC 7.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] NIST also is providing practical guidance and tools to better prepare facility owners, contractors, architects, engineers, emergency responders, and regulatory authorities to respond to future disasters.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] In November 2008, the investigation portion of the response plan was completed, with the release of the final report on 7 World Trade Center.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] The final report on the WTC Towers—including 30 recommendations for improving building and occupant safety—was released in October 2005.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] NIST works in conjunction with the Technical Guidelines Development Committee of the Election Assistance Commission to develop the Voluntary Voting System Guidelines for voting machines and other election technology.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] In February 2014, NIST published the NIST Cybersecurity Framework that serves as voluntary guidance for organizations to manage and reduce cybersecurity risk.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] It was later amended and Version 1.1 was published in April 2018.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] Executive Order 13800, Strengthening the Cybersecurity of Federal Networks and Critical Infrastructure, made the Framework mandatory for U.S. federal government agencies.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] An extension to the NIST Cybersecurity Framework is the Cybersecurity Maturity Model (CMMC) which was introduced in 2019 (though the origin of CMMC began with Executive Order 13556).
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] On August 25, 2025, the 48 CFR CMMC rule cleared regulatory review.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] According to ISI, it published on September 10, 2025.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] It emphasizes the importance of implementing Zero-trust architecture (ZTA) which focuses on protecting resources over the network perimeter.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] ZTA utilizes zero trust principles which include "never trust, always verify", "assume breach" and "least privileged access" to safeguard users, assets, and resources.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] Since ZTA holds no implicit trust to users within the network perimeter, authentication and authorization are performed at every stage of a digital transaction.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] This reduces the risk of unauthorized access to resources.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] NIST released a draft of the CSF 2.0 for public comment to November 4, 2023.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] NIST decided to update the framework to make it more applicable to small and medium size enterprises that use the framework, as well as to accommodate the constantly changing nature of cybersecurity.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] In August 2024, NIST released a final set of encryption tools designed to withstand the attack of a quantum computer.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] These post-quantum encryption standards secure a wide range of electronic information, from confidential email messages to e-commerce transactions that propel the modern economy.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] In May 2025, NIST announced the Moonlight data project to enhance satellite calibration.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] By providing precise measurements of the Moon's brightness, the initiative aims to improve the accuracy of Earth observation satellites, supporting applications such as agriculture, meteorology, and environmental monitoring.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] Four scientific researchers at NIST have been awarded Nobel Prizes for work in physics: William Daniel Phillips in 1997, Eric Allin Cornell in 2001, John Lewis Hall in 2005 and David Jeffrey Wineland in 2012, which is the largest number for any US government laboratory.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] All four were recognized for their work related to laser cooling of atoms, which is directly related to the development and advancement of the atomic clock.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] In 2011, Dan Shechtman was awarded the Nobel Prize in chemistry for his work on quasicrystals in the Metallurgy Division from 1982 to 1984.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] John Werner Cahn was awarded the 2011 Kyoto Prize for Materials Science.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] The National Medal of Science has been awarded to NIST researchers Cahn (1998) and Wineland (2007).
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] Since 1989, the director of NIST has been a Presidential appointee and is confirmed by the United States Senate.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] Since 1989, the average tenure of NIST directors has fallen from 11 years to 2 years in duration.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] Since the 2011 reorganization of NIST, the director also holds the title of Under Secretary of Commerce for Standards and Technology.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] Seventeen individuals have officially held the position, in addition to seven acting directors who have served on a temporary basis.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] NIST holds patents on behalf of the Federal government of the United States, with at least one of them being custodial to protect public domain use, such as one for a Chip-scale atomic clock, developed by a NIST team as part of a DARPA competition.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] Both papers report that the NSA worked covertly to get its own version of SP 800-90 approved for worldwide use in 2006.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] The whistle-blowing document states that "eventually, NSA became the sole editor".
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] The reports confirm suspicions and technical grounds publicly raised by cryptographers in 2007 that the EC-DRBG could contain a kleptographic backdoor (perhaps placed in the standard by NSA).
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] NIST responded to the allegations, stating that "NIST works to publish the strongest cryptographic standards possible" and that it uses "a transparent, public process to rigorously vet our recommended standards".
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] The agency stated that "there has been some confusion about the standards development process and the role of different organizations in it...The National Security Agency (NSA) participates in the NIST cryptography process because of its recognized expertise.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] Recognizing the concerns expressed, the agency reopened the public comment period for the SP800-90 publications, promising that "if vulnerabilities are found in these or any other NIST standards, we will work with the cryptographic community to address them as quickly as possible".
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] Due to public concern of this cryptovirology attack, NIST rescinded the EC-DRBG algorithm from the NIST SP 800-90 standard.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] In addition to these journals, NIST, and the National Bureau of Standards before it, has a robust technical reports publishing arm.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] NIST technical reports are published in several dozen series, which cover a wide range of topics, from computer technology to construction to aspects of standardization including weights, measures and reference data.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/national-institute-of-standards-and-technology] In addition to technical reports, NIST scientists publish many journal and conference papers each year; an database of these, along with more recent technical reports, can be found on the NIST website.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] The **NIST Cybersecurity Framework** (also known as **NIST CSF**), is a set of guidelines designed to help organizations assess and improve their preparedness against cybersecurity threats.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] National Institute of Standards and Technology, the framework has been adopted by cyber security professionals and organizations around the world.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] The NIST framework has provided a basis for communication and understanding of cybersecurity principles between organizations, both in the private sector and public, such as governments.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] The framework, which is publicly available online for free, provides recommendations of existing cybersecurity standards and actions that organizations can take to mitigate cybersecurity risk.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] The NIST CSF is made up of three overarching components: the CSF Core, CSF Organizational Profiles, and CSF Tiers.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] The CSF Core is divided into six functions, each focused on maximizing cybersecurity preparedness, improving communication, and mitigating risk.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] The six CSF Core functions include: Govern, Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, and Recover.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] These six core functions are then further broken down into subcategories.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] The CSF Organizational Profiles provide guidance on how organizations can assess themselves in terms of the CSF Core and where their cybersecurity practices can be improved and implemented.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] The CSF Tiers characterize and evaluate an organization's cybersecurity readiness and ability to mitigate risks.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] The CSF Tiers are helpful for organizations to know what level of cybersecurity protection they have in place and the processes behind the protection.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] After its publishment in 2014, the NIST CSF has been updated to reflect the most current cybersecurity practices.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] Among these updates is version 1.1, which was released in 2018.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] In version 1.1, changes were made to the framework to include supply chain risk management and new self-assessment processes.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] The current version of the NIST CSF is version 2.0, which was released in 2024.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] This current version introduced a new function to the CSF Core: Govern.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] Version 2.0 also increased the scope of the NIST CSF framework and its applicability to smaller organizations.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] Improvements to the framework language were also made, increasing its readability for non-technical audiences.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] The NIST Cybersecurity Framework is used internationally by organizations of varying sizes and sectors.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] Available for free to implement, NIST CSF sets cybersecurity guidelines and best practices for organizations to increase their defense against cyber threats and prepare for future risks.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] The NIST Cybersecurity Framework (CSF) is a set of guidelines developed by the U.S.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) to help organizations manage and mitigate cybersecurity risks.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] It draws from existing standards, guidelines, and best practices to provide a flexible and scalable approach to cybersecurity.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] The framework provides a high-level taxonomy of cybersecurity outcomes and offers a methodology for assessing and managing those outcomes.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] Additionally, it addresses the protection of privacy and civil liberties in a cybersecurity context.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] The CSF has been translated into multiple languages and is widely used by governments, businesses, and organizations across various sectors.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] According to a 2016 survey, 70% of organizations view the NIST Cybersecurity Framework as a best practice for computer security, though some have noted that implementation can require significant investment.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] The framework is designed to be flexible and adaptable, providing high-level guidance that allows individual organizations to determine the specifics of implementation based on their unique needs and risk profiles.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] Version 1.0 of the framework was published in 2014, primarily targeting operators of critical infrastructure.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] A public draft of Version 1.1 was released for comment in 2017, and the final version was published on April 16, 2018.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] Version 1.1 retained compatibility with the original framework while introducing additional guidance on areas such as supply chain risk management.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] Version 2.0 was released in 2024 and is the most current version of the NIST framework.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] This new version made significant updates to Version 1.1, by adding a "Govern" function to the CSF Core, expanding the framework's scope and applicability, and improving readability for non-technical stakeholders.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] The NIST Framework is made up of three main components: the CSF Core, CSF Organization Profiles, and CSF Tiers.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] The Core consists of six distinct functions, each contributing to a specific area of cybersecurity and risk management.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] These six functions are broken down into categories and subcategories.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] The Organization Profiles help organizations assess their current state of cybersecurity preparedness in terms of the CSF Core, and where improvements and adjustments can be made.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] The CSF Tiers help inform organizations on their current and target profiles in the CSF Organization Profiles.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] The CSF Tiers determine how rigorous an organization's current cybersecurity risk governance practices are and help to provide context for an organization's cybersecurity strategies and processes that are in place.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] Organizations typically start by developing a "Current Profile" to describe their existing cybersecurity practices and outcomes.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] From there, they can create a "Target Profile" to outline the desired future state and define the steps needed to achieve it.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] Alternatively, organizations can adopt a baseline profile based on their sector or specific industry needs.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] Research indicates that the NIST Cybersecurity Framework has the potential to influence cybersecurity standards both within the United States and internationally, particularly in sectors where formal cybersecurity standards are still emerging.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] This influence could foster better international cybersecurity practices, benefiting businesses that operate across borders and contributing to global cybersecurity efforts.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] In the healthcare sector, NIST has published Special Publication 800-66 Revision 2, which provides a detailed crosswalk mapping the HIPAA Security Rule requirements to the NIST CSF, enabling covered entities and business associates to use the framework for HIPAA compliance.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] The Core is one of the three overarching components of the NIST CSF.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] The Core is categorized into six functions, which are further divided into 22 categories.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] Each category is then further divided, amounting to a total of 106 subcategories of cybersecurity outcomes.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] Special Publications (SP) aside, most of the informative references requires a paid membership or purchase to access their respective guides.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] The cost and complexity of the framework has resulted in bills from both houses of Congress that direct NIST to create Cybersecurity Framework guides that are more accessible to small and medium businesses.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] Here are the functions and categories, along with their unique identifiers and definitions, as stated in the framework document.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] The Govern function is divided into six categories.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] Organizational Profiles are also part of the three overarching components of the NIST CSF.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] The Organizational Profiles provide guidance to organizations on how they can assess themselves in terms of the CSF Core and where they can improve and implement their cybersecurity practices according to their mission objectives, stakeholder expectations, the threat landscape, and other needs.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] This way, organizations can focus on specific areas of cybersecurity to meet their goals and communicate these changes to stakeholders.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] A **Target Profile:** describes the goals for cybersecurity risk management that an organization has selected to pursue.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] A Target Profile takes into account incoming changes to an organization's cybersecurity practices including new requirements, technology integration, and trends of threat intelligence.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] A Community Profile is a set of CSF outcomes that a group of organizations has selected to pursue to reach shared cybersecurity goals and interests.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] Community Profiles are commonly created for different sectors, technologies, threats, and other specific areas.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] Additionally, organizations can set a Community Profile as their Target Profile, creating an outline of improvements they can work towards together to improve their cybersecurity risk management.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] "Gather the information needed to prepare the Organizational Profile.": Organizations need to collect information before creating their Profile.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] Information can consist of organizational policies and rules, priorities for managing risk and resources, cybersecurity requirements, and other practices followed by an organization.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] "Create the Organizational Profile.": This step involves deciding what information the Profile will have based on the chosen CSF outcomes.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] This includes understanding the risks of the Current Profile and determining what improvements should be made to it to then create the Target Profile.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] An organization can use a Community Profile as their Target Profile.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] "Analyze the gaps between the Current and Target Profiles, and create an action plan.": After creating an Organizational Profile, organizations should analyze how their Current Profile and Target Profile differ and create a plan to achieve their Target Profile.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] "Implement the action plan, and update the Organizational Profile.": The final step is to act and follow the plan made in the previous step to achieve the Target Profile.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] The Target Profile can have a deadline that the organization has selected or remain an ongoing process.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] These steps can be repeated as many times as the organization desires to continuously improve their cybersecurity risk preparedness.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] The CSF Tiers are helpful for organizations to be informed of what level of cybersecurity protection they currently have and the processes behind the protection.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] The Tiers can be used to inform an organization's Current and Target Profiles.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] There are four Tiers which describe an organization's cybersecurity risk preparedness.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] The four Tiers include: Partial (Tier 1), Risk Informed (Tier 2), Repeatable (Tier 3), and Adaptive (Tier 4).
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] The Tiers provide guidance on how organizations can improve their cybersecurity practices by describing increasing levels of cybersecurity risk management.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] The Tiers can also be used to inform all people in an organization of the chosen level of cybersecurity practices, so employees are aware of the organization's security goals.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] Although the Tiers provide organizations with an overall evaluation of their cybersecurity preparedness, the Tiers should be used as a complement and not replace the Organizational Profiles.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] In 2021 NIST released Security Measures for "EO-Critical Software" Use Under Executive Order (EO) 14028 to outline security measures intended to better protect the use of deployed EO-critical software in agencies' operational environments.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] The NIST Cybersecurity Framework is meant to be a living document, meaning it will be updated and improved over time to keep up with changes in technology and cybersecurity threats, as well as to integrate best-practices and lessons learned.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] Since releasing version 1.1 in 2018, stakeholders have provided feedback that the CSF needed to be updated.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] In February 2022, NIST released a request for information on ways to improve the CSF, and released a subsequent concept paper in January 2023 with proposed changes.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] Most recently, NIST released its *Discussion Draft: The NIST Cybersecurity Framework 2.0 Core with Implementation Examples* and has requested public comments be submitted by November 4, 2023.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] Implementation examples have been added to provide practical and action-oriented processes to help users achieve the CSF subcategories.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] Additionally, the framework Profiles have been revised and expanded to demonstrate the various purposes of the profiles.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] A new Function, Govern, has been added to provide organizational context and the roles and responsibilities associated with developing a cybersecurity governance model.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] There is also an additional category in this Function focused on cybersecurity supply chain risk management.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/nist-cybersecurity-framework] The latest update also provides greater information on cybersecurity assessments by placing greater importance on the continuous improvement of security through a new Improvement Category in the Identify Function.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/risk-management-framework] The **Risk Management Framework** (RMF) is a United States federal government guideline, standard, and process for managing risk to help secure information systems (computers and networks).
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/risk-management-framework] The RMF was developed by the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST), and provides a structured process that integrates information security, privacy, and risk management activities into the system development life cycle.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/risk-management-framework] The RMF is an important aspect of a system's attainment of its Authority to Operate (ATO).
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/risk-management-framework] The primary document outlining the RMF is NIST Special Publication 800-37.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/risk-management-framework] The RMF steps link to several other NIST standards and guidelines, including NIST Special Publication 800-53.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/risk-management-framework] The Federal Information Security Management Act of 2002 (FISMA 2002) was enacted to safeguard U.S. economic and national security through improved information security.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/risk-management-framework] FISMA mandates the protection of information and information systems against unauthorized access, use, disclosure, disruption, modification, or destruction, ensuring confidentiality, integrity, and availability.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/risk-management-framework] Title III of FISMA 2002 tasked NIST with developing information security and risk management standards, guidelines, and requirements.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/risk-management-framework] In December 2019, revision 2 of the NIST Special Publication 800-37 was published, introducing a Prepare step to the overall process.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/risk-management-framework] Throughout its lifecycle, an information system will face various types of risk that can impact its security posture.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/risk-management-framework] The RMF process aids in the early identification and resolution of these risks.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/risk-management-framework] Broadly, risks can be classified as infrastructure, project, application, information asset, business continuity, outsourcing, external, and strategic risks.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/risk-management-framework] Infrastructure risks pertain to the reliability of computers and networks, while project risks involve budgeting, timelines, and system quality.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/risk-management-framework] Application risks relate to system performance and capacity.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/risk-management-framework] Information asset risks concern the potential loss or unauthorized disclosure of data.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/risk-management-framework] Business continuity risks focus on maintaining system reliability and uptime.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/risk-management-framework] Outsourcing risks involve the impact of third-party service providers on the system.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/risk-management-framework] External risks are factors beyond the information system's control that can impact the system's security.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/risk-management-framework] Strategic risks are associated with the need for information system functions to align with the business strategy that the system supports.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/risk-management-framework] Revision 2 also introduced a new "Prepare" step (step 0) to enhance the effectiveness, efficiency, and cost-effectiveness of the security and privacy risk management processes.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/security-controls] Systems of controls can be referred to as frameworks or standards.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/security-controls] Frameworks can enable an organization to manage security controls across different types of assets with consistency.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/security-controls] Security controls are to help reduce the likelihood or any impacts of security incidents and protect the CIA triad for the systems and the data.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/security-controls] While protecting it helps organizations meet its responsibilities; consistent risk management to systems, assets, data, networks and physical infrastructures.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/security-controls] Security controls can be classified by various criteria.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/security-controls] These classifications help organizations build a well designed multi-layered defense strategy, ensuring that they layers help control and prevent when threats are being taken placed.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/security-controls] Security controls include both technical controls (such as access management and fire walls) and administrative controls (including policies and procedures).
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/security-controls] Controls are part of risk treatment strategy which is applied after risk assessment and then design, building, operating, and changing them is a part of the lifecycle.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/security-controls] The **ISO/IEC 27000 series** standards promote good security practices and define frameworks or systems to structure the analysis and design for managing information security controls.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/security-controls] Most recent version, ISO/IEC 27001;2022, released in October 2022, specifies 93 controls organized some of the most well known standards are outlined below.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/security-controls] All organizations certified to ISO 27001:2013 are obliged to transition to the new version of the Standard within 3 years (by October 2025).
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/security-controls] The Federal Information Processing Standards (FIPS) apply to all US government agencies.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/security-controls] However, certain national security systems, under the purview of the Committee on National Security Systems, are managed outside these standards.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/security-controls] A maturity based framework divided into five functional areas and approximately 100 individual controls in its "core" and is widely used by U.S. organizations and government agencies.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/security-controls] A database of nearly one thousand technical controls grouped into families and cross references.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/security-controls] A proprietary control set published by ISACA.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/security-controls] Formerly known as the SANS Critical Security Controls now officially called the CIS Critical Security Controls (COS Controls).
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/security-controls] The CIS Controls are divided into 18 prioritized cybersecurity best practices that protect systems and data from threats.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/security-controls] The Controls are divided further into Implementation Groups (IGs) which are a recommended guidance to prioritize implementation of the CIS controls.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/security-controls] The intersection of security risk and laws that set standards of care is where data liability are defined.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/security-controls] A handful of databases are emerging to help risk managers research laws that define liability at the country, province/state, and local levels.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/security-controls] In these control sets, compliance with relevant laws are the actual risk mitigators.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/security-policy] If it is important to be secure, then it is important to be sure all of the security policy is enforced by mechanisms that are strong.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/security-policy] There are organized methodologies and risk assessment strategies to assure completeness of security policies and assure that they are completely enforced.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/security-policy] In complex systems, such as information systems, policies can be decomposed into sub-policies to facilitate the allocation of security mechanisms to enforce sub-policies.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/security-policy] It is too easy to simply go directly to the sub-policies, which are essentially the rules of operation and dispense with the top level policy.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/security-policy] That gives the false sense that the rules of operation address some overall definition of security when they do not.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/security-policy] Because it is so difficult to think clearly with completeness about security, rules of operation stated as "sub-policies" with no "super-policy" usually turn out to be rambling rules that fail to enforce anything with completeness.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/security-policy] Consequently, a top-level security policy is essential to any serious security scheme and sub-policies and rules of operation are meaningless without it.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/security-policy] Multiple regulatory and compliance frameworks mandate formal security policies as a foundational element of organizational information security programs.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/security-policy] These policies must be maintained in written form, reviewed periodically, and updated in response to environmental or operational changes.
[src:nist-cybersecurity-framework/security-policy] The ISO/IEC 27001 standard requires organizations to establish an information security policy appropriate to the purpose of the organization as a prerequisite for certification.
